  { q: 'Do Tampa homes even need reliable heating?', a: 'Yes — Tampa sees 5–15 nights per year below 40°F and has had hard freezes in January that dropped homes below 30°F inside when heating failed. Most Tampa homes run a heat pump or a heat-strip air handler, and both need annual service to stay reliable on the few nights they actually matter.' },
  { q: 'What\'s the difference between a heat pump and a furnace?', a: 'A heat pump uses the same refrigerant cycle as your AC — just reversed — to move warmth into the home, very efficiently down to about 35°F ambient. Below that, most Tampa heat pumps switch on electric-resistance heat strips as backup. Furnaces (gas or propane) are rare in Florida and only used in some northern-Tampa Bay new-construction areas.' },
